Text squares.

A text square is a silent sign. The player stands on it, presses the interact key, and it speaks the text you wrote — exactly the way a sign does — but with no sound of its own, no theme to choose, and nothing that can destroy it. It's the entity for plain spoken text tied to a place when you don't want any audio dressing or a breakable object: a quiet label, a readable note, an invisible plaque.

A text square is built in two variants, chosen from the build mode list: a single text square (one tile) and a ranged text square (a rectangular area the player can read from anywhere inside).

How a text square works.

A text square covers its tile or area and does exactly one thing: while the player is inside it and presses the interact key, it speaks its text. There is no press cue, no ambient loop, and no break sound — just the words. It can't be destroyed and has no audio to configure.

How a text square differs from a sign.

The two read their text on a press in the same way, so the difference is entirely about everything around the text:

A sign carries a sound theme — a press cue, an optional ambient loop — and can be made destroyable, so it announces itself and can be broken.
A text square strips all of that away: no sound theme, no press cue, no loop, no destroyable option. It's the area and the words and nothing else.

Reach for a text square when you want plain, silent readable text; reach for a sign when you want audio feedback when it's read, an ambient loop to find it by, or an object the player can smash. See the signs topic.

Text square fields.

The text square form takes the following:

Coordinates. A single text square takes an x and y (and z on 3d maps); a ranged text square takes a minimum and maximum x and y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), chosen with the ranged option in the build mode list.

Text. The message spoken when the player reads the text square.

A text square has no sound and no other settings — its area and its text are the whole of it.

Authoring text squares by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a single text square is: text_square x y "text". On 3d maps a z follows y: text_square x y z "text". A ranged text square replaces the single tile with minimum and maximum pairs: text_square minx maxx miny maxy "text", inserting a minimum and maximum z after the y pair on 3d maps. The text is wrapped in double quotes so it may contain spaces.
